data.name: label4.Text
data.value: Streaming Mode: [Default Buffered] - Buffered: optimize commands streaming filling up grbl receive buffer [recommended] - Synchronous: wait for the execution of each command prior to send the very next command [slower but safer] - RepeatOnError: same as Synchronous but repeat commands if detect error [experimental]

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: Connection Protocol: - UsbSerial, is the most common protocol. Should be used if your engraver is connected to USB or COM port. - Telnet, if you have a WiFi-Telnet bridge. Communication is implemented like a simple telnet client-server. - LaserWebESP8266 support WiFi connection via WebSocket. Compatible with LaserWeb-ESP8266 software.

data.name: label6.Text
data.value: Threading Mode: UltraFast, Fast, Quiet, Slow. [Default UltraFast] This setting affect the speed of sending thread and the frequency of status report request. Set slower values if you are experiencing issues.

data.name: label7.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL can detect issues and warn the user providing info about how to solve them. If disabled all the issues are silently managed without warning.

data.name: label2.Text
data.value: If enabled LaserGRBL send a soft-reset when the connection to grbl is opened.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: If enabled LaserGRBL send a hard-reset when the connection to grbl is opened. [Position is lost!]

data.name: label9.Text
data.value: Firmware type - Grbl: the awesome firmware for which LaserGRBL was developed for. - Smoothie [experimental]: support has been added recently and is not fully tested.

data.name: label1.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL use power modulation through G-Code "S command" to produce grayscale tones. Your laser must support TTL control connected to arduino PIN D11. If not, please disable PWM support.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: By default LaserGRBL produces engraving lines in both travel directions of the laser head. Some tests have shown that this mode (which is faster) produces lower quality results. If the maximum marking quality is desired, activate this option.

data.name: label10.Text
data.value:
Without "Continuous Jog" when jog button is pressed LaserGRBL send Jog request with settled speed and movement; and the jog is fully executed to the final position. If you enable "Continuous Jog" jogging is sent with mouse-down and aborted/interrupted on mouse-up, so you can do approximative positioning but in a very comfortable way.
NOTE: "Continuous Jog" only work with Grbl v1.1 or later, and require table size is correctily configured in Grbl Configuration (Menu "Grbl" -> "Grbl Configuration" $130, $131, $132)

data.name: label11.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL is not designed to support Z axis, but if you have a 3axis hardware maybe you could find this option usefull.

data.name: label20.Text
data.value: Time OFF: after this cooling time LaserGRBL will send a resume command to continue engraving job.

data.name: label12.Text
data.value: Some laser diode can heat-up to much if they run for a long time at the highest power. To prevent diode overheating and increase your laser lifetime you can add some automatic cooling-down cycles that insert some pause during engraivng process. If Auto Cooling is enabled LaserGRBL will send automatic "feed hold" and "job resume" according with ON-OFF timing configuration.

data.name: label13.Text
data.value: Time ON: this is the maximum time that Laser will stay on during engraving process. After this time LaserGRBL will send an automatic feed hold to cool down the laser.

data.name: label21.Text
data.value: Warning: this feature will work only with grbl versions > v1.1 with "laser mode" enabled. If you use auto-cooling with older grbl version (or with laser mode disabled) the laser will not turn off during pauses and burns holes in your work!
